{
  "texts": [
    "The above gives a free field description of the sl(2, R) 1 ⊕ su(2) 1 theory.",
    "It is a remarkable fact that this content is already rich enough to describe the full supersymmetric theory and provides an elegant way to avoid the unitarity issues that emerge in conventional attempts to give an RNS description of the k = 1 theory [3,7].",
    "Indeed, it has been shown [3,7] (see also appendix A of [37]) that the full psu(1, 1|2) 1 algebra is generated by the free fields in the action (2.3), with the supercurrents S αA± (z) realised byS αA+ = ξ α χ A, S αA-= -η α ψ A, (2.4)which combine with the bosonic currents K a (z) and J a (z) to give the superalgebra u(1, 1|2) 1.Note that the currents S αA± (z) are also invariant under the scaling symmetries (2.1) and (2.2) when performed simultaneously, so that this scaling invariance is a property of the full supersymmetric theory.",
    "We could choose to view the scalings (2.1) and (2.2) as independent symmetries, generated by the u(1) currentsU = - 1 2 (η + ξ --η -ξ +), V = - 1 2 (χ + ψ --χ -ψ +).It is often convenient to define the new basisZ = U + V and Y = U -V for which Z(z)Z(w) ∼ 0, Y (z)Y (w) ∼ 0, Z(z)Y (w) ∼ -1 (z -w) 2.We can recover the desired psu(1, 1|2) 1 theory viapsu(1, 1|2) 1 ∼ = u(1, 1|2) 1 u(1) U ⊕ u(1) V, (2.5)by quotienting out the two u(1) currents.",
    "Since these u(1) currents have non-trivial OPEs with themselves, this quotient is slightly non-trivial."
  ]
}